# Brainstorming — Design Before Code
# Source: github.com/obra/superpowers | License: MIT

## When to Use
Use BEFORE any implementation. Triggers on: "let's build X", "I want to add X",
"design X", "how should we approach X", "plan X", "new feature", "new module",
"architect X", "think through X". Also: any ambiguous request where requirements
aren't fully specified. If there's even 10% chance this applies, invoke it first.

## HARD GATE
Do NOT invoke any implementation skill, write any code, scaffold any project,
or take any implementation action until you have presented a design and the
user has explicitly approved it.

---

## Workflow

### Step 1 — Explore Context
Before asking anything, read:
- CLAUDE.md (project constraints, existing patterns)
- Relevant existing files (don't assume — check)
- Recent git history for related changes

### Step 2 — Clarifying Questions
Ask one question at a time. Prefer multiple-choice over open-ended.
Stop when you have enough to propose approaches.

Example good question:
> "Should this work for unauthenticated users, or only logged-in tutores?"
> a) Only authenticated users
> b) Public with rate limiting
> c) Both, with different feature sets

### Step 3 — Propose 2–3 Approaches
For each approach, state:
- What it does
- Main trade-off
- Your recommendation and why

Apply YAGNI ruthlessly — cut anything the user hasn't asked for.

### Step 4 — Present Design in Sections
Don't dump the full design at once. Present section by section, get approval:
- Data model
- API surface
- UI/UX flow
- Edge cases

### Step 5 — Write Spec
Save to: `docs/superpowers/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-<topic>-design.md`

Include:
- Goal (one sentence)
- Constraints (from CLAUDE.md + user input)
- Chosen approach + rationale
- Data model changes
- API changes
- UI changes
- Out of scope (explicit)
- Open questions

### Step 6 — Self-Review Spec
Check for:
- [ ] Placeholders ("TBD", "TODO") → resolve them
- [ ] Contradictions with CLAUDE.md constraints
- [ ] Ambiguous language → make concrete
- [ ] Missing edge cases

### Step 7 — Request User Review
Present the spec file path and ask for approval before proceeding.

### Step 8 — Invoke writing-plans
Only after explicit approval: dispatch `/writing-plans` with the spec as input.

---

## Principles
- One question per message
- Always explore alternatives before committing
- Scale documentation to actual complexity (small feature = short spec)
- Visual companion (diagrams) only when text is insufficient
- Never skip this step because the task "seems simple"
